üë®‚Äçüéì A. Student Routes
POST /api/students/register ‚Äî Register a new student
GET /api/students ‚Äî Get all registered students

Request Example:
{ "name": "John Doe", "email": "john@example.com", "matricNumber": "U2021/12345" }
üó≥Ô∏è B. Election Routes
POST /api/elections ‚Äî Create a new election
GET /api/elections ‚Äî List all elections

Request Example:
{ "title": "Student Union Election 2025", "description": "Election for student body positions" }
üë§ C. Candidate Routes
POST /api/candidates ‚Äî Add a candidate to an election
GET /api/candidates ‚Äî Get all candidates
GET /api/candidates/:electionId ‚Äî Get all candidates in a specific election

Request Example:
{ "name": "Alice Johnson", "department": "Computer Science", "electionId": 1 }
üßæ D. Voting Routes
POST /api/votes ‚Äî Cast a vote for a candidate
GET /api/results/:electionId ‚Äî Get election results (vote counts per candidate)

Request Example:
{ "studentId": 1, "candidateId": 3, "electionId": 1 }

Voting Rules:
- A student can vote only once per election.
- Each vote must be linked to both a student and a candidate.
3Ô∏è‚É£ Controller Responsibilities
Each controller file should import data arrays from data/data.js, implement logic for each route, and send responses using res.json().

Example (studentController.js):

const { students } = require('../data/data');

let studentId = 1;

exports.registerStudent = (req, res) => {
  const { name, email, matricNumber } = req.body;
  const newStudent = { id: studentId++, name, email, matricNumber };
  students.push(newStudent);
  res.json({ message: 'Student registered successfully', student: newStudent });
};

exports.getAllStudents = (req, res) => {
  res.json(students);
};
4Ô∏è‚É£ Route Example
Example (studentRoutes.js):

const express = require('express');
const router = express.Router();
const { registerStudent, getAllStudents } = require('../controllers/studentController');

router.post('/register', registerStudent);
router.get('/', getAllStudents);

module.exports = router;

In server.js:

const express = require('express');
const app = express();
const studentRoutes = require('./routes/studentRoutes');
const electionRoutes = require('./routes/electionRoutes');
const candidateRoutes = require('./routes/candidateRoutes');
const voteRoutes = require('./routes/voteRoutes');

app.use(express.json());
app.use('/api/students', studentRoutes);
app.use('/api/elections', electionRoutes);
app.use('/api/candidates', candidateRoutes);
app.use('/api/votes', voteRoutes);

const PORT = 3000;
app.listen(PORT, () => console.log(`Server running on port ${PORT}`));
